        "text": "Public roads through enclosed common land were made to an accepted width between boundaries. In the late eighteenth century this was at least 60 feet (18&nbsp;m), but from the 1790s this was decreased to 40 feet (12&nbsp;m), and later 30 feet (9.1&nbsp;m) as the normal maximum width. The reason for these wide roads to was to prevent excessive churning of the road bed, and allow easy movement of flocks and herds of animals.<ref name=\"whyte\">Transforming Fell and Valley, Ian Whyte. Published by Centre for North West regional Studies, University of Lancaster 2003</ref>"
